This article discusses the need for a next-generation, interoperable system for public safety communications in the United States. The limitations of current systems were highlighted during 9/11 and Hurricane Katrina, where first responders were unable to communicate effectively with each other. The article explains that traditional public safety devices and networks are outdated and do not compare to those provided by modern commercial cellular operators. The President's Wireless Innovation and Infrastructure Initiative aims to develop and deploy a nationwide wireless broadband network for first responders, allowing them to benefit from innovative applications and replace their legacy communications infrastructure. The benefits of such a network include greater interoperability, cost savings, unlocking the potential of commercial devices, and better performance through innovation. The article also provides background information on the President's Wireless Initiative, which aims to drive investment and innovation in next-generation wireless technologies for public safety.